SIMPLE: hose
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hose
<hw>Hose</hw> <pr>(h⟦omac⟧z)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Hose</plw>, formerly <plw>Hosen</plw> <pr>(h⟦omac⟧"z'n)</pr>.</plu>
<ety>[AS. <ets>hose</ets>; akin to D. <ets>hoos</ets>, G.
<ets>hose</ets> breeches, OHG. <ets>hosa</ets>, Icel. <ets>hosa</ets>
stocking, gather, Dan. <ets>hose</ets> stocking; cf. Russ.
<ets>koshulia</ets> a fur jacket.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Close-fitting
trousers or breeches, as formerly worn, reaching to the knee.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These men were bound in their coats, their <qex>hosen</qex>, and
their hats, and their other garments.</q> <rj><qau>Dan. iii.
21.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His youthful <qex>hose</qex>, well saved, a world too wide⟦br⟧
For his shrunk shank.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Covering for the feet and lower part of the legs; a
stocking or stockings.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A flexible pipe, made of leather, India rubber, or
other material, and used for conveying fluids, especially water, from a
faucet, hydrant, or fire engine.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Hose carriage</b></col>, <col><b>Hose
cart</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Hose truck</b></col></mcol>, <cd>a
wheeled vehicle fitted for conveying hose for extinguishing fires.</cd>
-- <col><b>Hose company</b></col>, <cd>a company of men appointed to
bring and manage hose in the extinguishing of fires.</cd>
<mark>[U.S.]</mark> -- <col><b>Hose coupling</b></col>, <cd>coupling
with interlocking parts for uniting hose, end to end.</cd> --
<col><b>Hose wrench</b></col>, <cd>a spanner for turning hose couplings,
to unite or disconnect them.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hosen</ent>⟦br⟧
